author: Jonathon Moran
title: Elizabeth Debicki honoured with Australian’s in Film award for her ‘varied and interesting’ career
text:
ELIZABETH Debicki sums up her career to date as “varied and interesting”.
As one of our biggest exports to Hollywood since making her feature film debut in A Few Best Men in 2011, Debicki is being honoured with the Australian’s in Film breakthrough award at a ceremony in Los Angeles on Sunday.
“I would describe it as varied,” she said of her body of work so far. “I am really lucky that the things that I’ve done have all been so very different from each other, I think I actively seek that out but to a certain extent you are not in control of the things that come your way as an actor. It makes my life interesting.”
Cate Blanchett and Debicki in The Maids. Picture: Supplied Debicki, 25, is about to start shooting The Tale in Louisiana with Ellen Burstyn and Laura Dern.
It’s the latest in a string of big films on her resume that includes Baz Luhrmann’s The Great Gatsby, The Man From U.N.C.L.E., Everest and Macbeth.
“I haven’t met them yet but I’m sure I’ll be totally starstruck,” she said.

Opinion 0 comments Robert Irwin’s animal instinct Celebrity Also coming up for Debicki is British TV series The Night Manager with Hugh Laurie and Aussie TV drama The Kettering Incident that will air on Foxtel’s SoHo channel.
Even before her acting profile grew, top end designers clamoured to dress the 190cm tall Debicki.
Actors Matthew Le Nevez and Debicki who will both play roles in The Kettering Incident. She last week attended the Miu Miu show at Paris Fashion week and dined with Muiccia Prada.
“I guess I don’t think of myself as someone who is inherently fashionable,” she said.
“I just find it such a fascinating world. I suppose I find how much I enjoy it surprising in a sense. Some designers want to dress me because I am tall and we can do outrageous shape things you couldn’t necessarily do with someone shorter.”
Elizabeth Debicki in a scene from film The Man From UNCLE. There is an upside to fashion Debicki is only realising now.
“You can kind of use it to your advantage as an actor because it can be a bit of a circus,” she said.
“While the focus is about the film, you can have a little forum to express something about yourself so if you find a designer you can align yourself with who does that in their work, you should keep the good thing going.
“All of that red carpet stuff can be quite daunting so if you feel good about yourself, you find it a smoother process and you feel a lot more confident going out there and doing that stuff.”
High heels and dresses are generally not for Debicki though.
“I generally view heels as a slightly not evolved form of foot binding,” she said. “They’re not comfortable and they’re bad for your back. I don’t have the stamina for it.”
